figgy.title: Investigate Adding InCommon as an Authorization Provider

comments.body: We decided that InCommon is too complex and hits too few of our users. The research we've done will be useful if we find a need for a cross-institution shared experience.

The two staging servers are done:
figgy-db-staging1: lib-vmserv01a, 4 CPU, 80+30GB hard drives, 64GB memory
figgy-db-staging2: lib-vmserv03a, 4 CPU, 80+30GB hard drives, 64GB memory

First round on the two prod servers is done. Still need refinement, but for today:
figgy-db-prod1: lib-vmserv03b, 8 CPU, 30+300+200GB hard drives, 128GB memory
figgy-db-prod2: lib-vmserv02a, 8 CPU, 80+300GB hard drives, 128GB memory

figgy.title: Wireframe user optimized Virtual Reading Room path options

comments.body: Without some type of login, how will we track which items an individual uses? I think there needs to be some kind of authorization to do this. I like the phone number login as it seems like it makes for quick access but still allows us to monitor their use.

> Without some type of login, how will we track which items an individual uses?

Yeah, I think that option (click through only) is about us considering if we can get away not tracking users that granularly.

It's more awkward, but I'm warming up to the Aeon option if only because it means we avoid having to write a bunch of reporting logic in the future - all requests for special collections are in Aeon. So just seeing the variety of options from a user perspective might help us decide what trade offs to make
Aeon sounds like a good option for moving forward. And it would be great if we don't have to track the use like that.
